   SIGNIFICANT ACTIVITIES
      CALS PILOT PROJECT 
         A meeting was held with the principal participants of the CALS pilot 
         to discuss status of the Phase I effort and potential expansion in a 
         Phase II follow-on.  The exposure to a structured document with its 
         capability for viewing and linking has raised the possibility of a 
         hypertext approach to management of major document repositories.  Such
         a scenario requires interfaces to major CALS data sources, i.e. DB2, 
         IMS, CATI, etc.  Subsequent discussion of the pilot activity with CALS
         management made it clear that such a scenario was desirable, but that 
         the scope of the current pilot is to gain experience in use of a 
         hypertext system for document generation, not conceive of mechanisms 
         to tie things together, that is the intent of CALS itself.  A data 
         modeling activity addressing CALS documents was discussed as a 
         possible follow-on task. {TDC}
      DEC/MDC JOINT ACTIVITIES 
         A meeting was held in John Dutton's office with representatives from 
         Digital Equipment Corp. to discuss joint activities based on the 
         Augment technologies and concepts.  DEC has interest in helping 
         support and learn from the MDC pilot projects, and in helping raise 
         the visibility of the Teaming and Collaboration project within MDC.  
         Alternatives for extending the current Agreement in Principle to a 
         more explicit and binding agreement were proposed and are being 
         pursued. {TDC}
         George Metes and Scott Huchingson from DEC spent two days at MDC 
         discussing alternative scenarios for joint tasks.  A primary concern 
         of both companies is the success of the MDC pilot projects and the 
         harvesting of information and knowledge from them. {TDC}
         A meeting was held on 11 April between Brad Rigdon and Dave Carter 
         from MDC and Ulf Fagerquist, Nils Norren, George Metes, and Scott 
         Huchingson from DEC.  DEC indicated a change in philosophy since the 
         last meeting with Brad, stating an interest in porting Augment 
         software from the current platform to a VAX platform, specifically 
         requiring a workstation capability. {TDC}
         Discussions were held with Brooks Sharp of the Navy CAD/CAM Project 
         and Dave Bundy of the CAT Project about participation in the rehosting
         of the Augment front-end software.  Both are interested in continued 
         discussion in this area. {TDC}
         A meeting was held in Boston with DEC to refine the plans for joint 
         effort. Time was spent working on the "process" which will be used to 
         develop the business plan and the detailed task items.  This process 
         will be used within DEC to refine their internal plan which will be 
         explained to MDC representative during the week of 9 May. {TDC}
      DECSYSTEM 2065 
         The DECsystem 2065 is installed and was turned over to MDC Mar 21.  
         Minor problems have been identified and are being worked.  
         Establishing appropriate communications appears to be progressing 
         slowly.  Tymnet, DEC, MDAIS, and ASD are working to resolve problems. 
         {DFY}
         The TOPS-20 operating system has been loaded and the Augment system 
         has been installed.  Mating the resulting system to the specific STL 
         communication configuation is now the pacing item.  Meeting  with DEC 
         on Apr 15 to discuss 2065 problems -- tape drive replacement, spare 
         RP06, NIA20 Ethernet interface, etc. went well.  DEC will assist in 
         obtaining a replacement tape drive, NIA20, and spare RPO6 disp packs. 
         {DFY}
         An Augment system is being installed on a DECsystem 20 at Stanford 
         University to host an electronic forum of companies interested in 
         communicating on Teaming and Collaboration.
      DEFENSE DATA NETWORK (DDN) 
         A meeting was held with the individuals who have been seeking a way to
         continue conectivity to the DDN after the Information Systems Company 
         (ISC) shuts down the Augment product area.  We have offered the St. 
         Louis DECsystem 2065 as a near term way to continue the current 
         hardware/software connection mechanism.  Keith Hacke and Bartow 
         Lammert have succeeded in obtaining a long term sponsorship agreement 
         from AVSCOM if we can provide connectivity to the Helicopter Company. 
         No definite plan has emerged. {TDC}
      DOCUMENT COORDINATION / JOURNAL LINK MANAGEMENT 
         Wrote proposal / partial spec. to introduce more powerful, dynamic 
         operations for viewing the relationships and cross-references possible
         between items in Augment journals. {JCC}
      E-MAIL TASK FORCE 
         The E-mail task force, a part of the larger activity to implement the 
         corporate office automation architecture, met to discuss progress.  
         The scope of this effort is to implement interfaces between major MDC 
         mail systems.  After the implementation of various vendor products, 
         integration needs will be addressed. {TDC}
      MACINTOSH 
         Developed, tested, and documented (outline only) a procedure for 
         information exchange between AUGMENT and the Macintosh <TAC,860,>.  
         This procedure is for ASCII text only files. {DAP}
      MENUMAIL 
         A version of the Augment Mail System was generated which provides a 
         lotus-type menu interface.  The architecture of the Augment front-end 
         allowed the first prototype to be generated in a week-end.  On-line 
         dialog continues to discuss "Menumail" and its relationship to NASP 
         training needs.  {SGK}
      MERGING TEXT AND GRAPHICS 
         INSET, the text and graphics integration package from InSet Systems 
         Inc., allows the insertion of images stored on the workstation into 
         printout from AUGMENT or MiniBASE.  InSet can -- {DAP}
            Capture screen images from most applications on the IBM PC {DAP}
            InSet provides a complete graphics editor to modify and create your
            own images at any time {DAP}
            InSet allows you to paste images into your reports.Brm=80; {DAP}
            InSet will even let you preview your images and text together in 
            your word processor {DAP}
            InSet lets you print your documents as you normally do and merges 
            your images automatically into your reports {DAP}
            InSet can take your complete document, including graphics, and pack
            it into a format that you can send over electronic mail services. 
            {DAP}
         This package has been tested and works as advertized. {DAP}
      NASP PILOT PROJECT 
         Discussions with the NASP participants continue.  We have made an 
         offer to collocate on the NASP Project in order to provide more 
         support and gain more contact time necessary to determine project 
         needs.  NASP management is selling the Augment approach for project 
         coordination to the cocontractors.  Accounts are being established for
         individuals at Rocketdyne, Pratt & Whitnety, North American, and 
         General Dynamics.  Cost effective mechanisms for training are being 
         investigated. {TDC}
         A meeting was held with the NASP administrative staff.  We learned 
         that the relationships with the other Materials Development 
         contractors are not by contract; they are all independently contracted
         to the Air Force.  But they are coordinating through a memo of 
         understanding, with joint agreement that MCAIR will take the lead.  A 
         mailbox has been provided to the MDC project on the WPAFB All-in-One 
         system.  Thus far no use has been made of it, and no plans for use 
         exist.  An offer was made to the project to provide "dumb" terminals 
         to them to get connectivity established.  They are going to accept the
         offer. {TDC}
         A meeting was held with Charlie Cassmeyer to discuss access to the 
         Defense Data Network through Augment.  Cass has to communicate with 
         personnel at WPAFB through the DDN and has not been able to 
         successfully accomplish it yet.  We will establish links for him and 
         help him become familiar with procedures.  A memo stating NASP 
         requirements for use of the DDN was obtained and forwarded to MCAIR 
         Telecommunications. {TDC}
         NASP personnel have received personalized tutoring/coaching.  Areas of
         specialized interest are developing that will help in advancing the 
         use of Augment within NASP.  Report generation, mail, and file 
         transfer capabilities appear to be receiving the most attention. {DFY}
      NETWORK COMPUTING FORUM 
         A meeting was held on the CAT Project with the leaders of the Computer
         Systems Integration Project, a corporate common project.  The CSI 
         project sees similarity between their goals and those of the Network 
         Computing Forum and wanted to discuss ways to gain benefits from NCF 
         activity.  Further meetings are planned. {TDC}
         The meeting of the NCF Steering Committee was attended.  Progress was 
         made in establishing the NCF as a self supporting legal entity.  More 
         than 100 people have pre-registered for the May NCF meeting, with 
         projection of 165 to 200 attendees.  The format of the meeting has 
         been changed, with less emphasis placed on "working" groups, who are 
         responsible for a deliverable, and more being placed on interest 
         groups who may need only to meet and discuss similar technical 
         problems related to networked computing.  This is more consistent with
         our experience in the User Interface group, where people are intensely
         interested, but little time can be allocated to actually "work" on a 
         NCF deliverable. {TDC}
      TAC ADMINISTRATION 
         A re-write of Command Sequence was completed which allows 
         consolidation of past journaled Weekly Reports into a single Monthly 
         report.  Some finishing touches are still needed to deal with Journal 
         items that have been archived and Directive/Format-field interplay 
         when sent to PROFS -- should be ready for release in time for the 
         April report. {DLS}
         Management of resources (people, time & dollars) is being undertaken 
         in an electronic environment as part of the TAC project.  Reporting on
         tech/admin accomplishments and time expenditures are underway via the 
         weekly activity reports and timecards.  A procedure and forms for 
         filing expense claims are being developed to begin the process of 
         getting a handle on dollar expenditures. {DLS}
         Agreement has been reached with accounting personnel in the Computer 
         Systems Company, the Network Systems Company, and MDAIS to transfer 
         all TAC charges to the MDAIS M&I charge number.  On-line time charge 
         summaries that are resident in Augment will then be used to define the
         transfer of charges to appropriate DSA, NASP, CALS, or other project 
         charge numbers.  This is the only effective way to handle the transfer
         of charges from ISC to MDAIS. {TDC}
         A review of the Teaming and collaboration Project was held with 
         Wendell Jones of the Corporate IRM staff.  Wendell is responsible for 
         strategic IRM planning and corporate telecommunications.  Although the
         concepts described in our architecture are familiar to Wendell, the 
         notion of co-evolution of technology and organizations in a directed 
         manner was new and will require follow-up sessions to more completely 
         explain.  In the future, Wendell will participate in the DEC/MDC 
         discussions. {TDC}
         Conversations were held with representatives from Washington 
         University, Boeing Computer Services (Space Station), and Jet 
         Propulsion Laboratory to explain our project and results thus far. 
         {TDC}
         Project personnel have made substantial contacts within industry, in 
         addition to DEC, to explain the MDC concepts of basic computer 
         infrastructure and coevolution of the organization with technology.  A
         synopsis of the major contacts includes:
